            <div><opener><salute>Dear Sir</salute></opener>
                
                <p>I seize the first opportunity of sending you &amp; my fellow travellers a sketch of my journey please to communicate it to them 
                    with my best compliments. if you take the same route down, please to add y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> remarks &amp; sketch 
                    the arms, especially those above &amp; below the Religious in <placeName ref="pl1349">Luton Church</placeName>.<note type="editorial">
                        This refers to the tomb at Luton church described by Pennant as being in the form of an altar, with 'various arms' on top, and the 
                        'effigies of William Wenlock, in the habit of a shaven priest', lying on it. The arms, 'a small shield of a chevron, between three 
                        croslet gules' enclosing a Latin imprecation addressed to the virgin Mary and Jesus ('Salve Regina Mater miserecordie | Jesu 
                        fili Dei miser[er]e mei'; Hail Queen, Mother of mercy, Jesus, Son of God, have mercy on me), placed 'on a label from his mouth'. 
                        <hi rend="italic">The journey from Chester to London</hi> (1782), pp. 397–8.
                    </note> In respect to the tomb at <placeName ref="pl1360">acton</placeName> it is of a 
                    <persName ref="pe0813">Sir W<hi rend="superscript">m</hi> de Manwaring</persName>, the date defaced, but you may recover it by consulting 
                    <bibl type="authorial"><title ref="bi0616">Holme's collections ab<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>. cheshire</title></bibl> in the <placeName ref="pl1236">museum</placeName>. 
                    Let me beg you w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> search for what is said ab<hi rend="superscript">t</hi> <placeName ref="pl1349">Luton Ch.</placeName> 
                    also. should you or my friends be able to give me any anecdotes relating to any of the places I now inform you of, I shall be happy to receive 
                    them. you will oblige me by sending one of <persName ref="pe0373">Buck</persName>'s lists &amp; inclose it in a frank: when <persName ref="pe0015">Sir Roger</persName> 
                    arrives I shall take care to get some for you; but I hope you will not be long before you give us y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> company. 
                    <persName ref="pe0234">Bel</persName> <persName ref="pe0065">Davy</persName> &amp; <persName ref="pe0812">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Falconer</persName> 
                    present best complim<hi rend="superscript">ts</hi>. the two first very thankfull for y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> kind remembrance. I am Dear Sir</p>
                
              
                <closer><salute>Most affect<hi rend="superscript">ly</hi> y<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>
                </salute>
                    <signed><persName ref="pe0232">Tho Pennant</persName></signed>
                    <dateline><placeName ref="pl0002">Chester</placeName> april 27<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1773</dateline></closer>
                
                <postscript><p>I go to <placeName ref="pl0001">Downing</placeName> this week.
                 
                </p>
                    <p>   
                        Turn over.
                        </p>
                    <p>Be so good as to desire <persName ref="pe0104">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Gough</persName> to leave 
                        my m<gap reason="illegible" unit="letters" quantity="1"/>y drawings at 
                        <persName ref="pe0026">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Whites</persName>, for they 
                        must be soon engraven. I mean those that are with the Antiquaries.<note type="editorial">A reference to 
                            the Society of Antiquaries of London and its members.</note></p></postscript>
            </div>
            
